{
  "text": "To illustrate, [CITATION_1] identified four markers of career success: human capital (e.g. education and job tenure), organizational sponsorship (e.g. organizational and supervisor support), personal traits (e.g. extraversion and openness) and socio-demographic attributes (e.g. marital status and age). Conversely, [CITATION_2] defined career success as self-referent (own) and other referent (in comparison with others) achievements, and [CITATION_3] identified three types of career success -material, psychological and social. Finally, [CITATION_4] critiqued conceptual and methodological shortcomings of career success and provided more 'inclusive' conceptualization suitable for general managers, with nine dimensions: work performance, advancement, self-development, creativity, security, satisfaction, recognition, cooperation and contribution.",
  "correct_citation": {
